China Stocks: Gezhouba, Shanghai Mechanical, Zijin Mining

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-07-14T07:43:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-14/china-stocks-gezhouba-shanghai-mechanical-zijin-mining.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3 p.m. local time.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, gained 14.97 points, or 0.5 percent, to
2,810.44. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  rose 0.3 percent to 3,115.75.  Commodity producers: Zijin Mining Group Co. (601899 CH),
the nation’s biggest producer of bullion, jumped 6.3 percent to
5.78 yuan, the highest since Dec. 7. Jiangxi Copper Co. (600362
CH), the largest copper producer, rose 2.8 percent to 37.08
yuan. China Shenhua Energy Co. (601088 CH), the largest coal
producer, gained 0.4 percent to 30.4 yuan.  Global commodity prices climbed to a four-week high after
U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman  Ben S. Bernanke  said he is
prepared to provide additional stimulus to boost the economy.
Euro Pacific Capital Inc. predicted gold may surge to $2,000 an
ounce if the Fed starts a third round of U.S. debt purchases.
Spot gold rose to a record $1,589.80 today.  Escalator manufacturers: Shanghai Mechanical & Electrical
Industry Co. (600835 CH) gained 4.4 percent to 13.90 yuan, the
highest since April 13. Canny Elevator Company Ltd. (002367 CH)
rose 1.2 percent to 18.21 yuan.  Chinese companies may benefit from a nationwide halt in the
use of escalators produced by United Technologies Corp.’s Otis
unit after an incident in Beijing last week, the 21st Century
Business Herald reported today.       China Gezhouba Group Co. (600068 CH): The water conservancy
projects contractor fell 1.8 percent to 12.08 yuan. China
Construction Bank Corp. (601939 CH) sold 35 million shares, or
1.01 percent of the company, from Nov. 11 to July 12.
Construction Bank gained 0.8 percent to 4.88 yuan.  XCMG Construction Machinery Co. (000425 CH): China’s
biggest crane maker rose 1.7 percent to 24.99 yuan, the biggest
gain since July 1. The company said net income for the first
half may have increased as much as 60 percent to 2.2 billion
yuan.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net  